  "prompt": "Why does a salt solution conduct electricity?",
  "response": "A salt solution conducts electricity because it contains ions that are free to move and carry electric charge. Here's a more detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Dissociation of Salt**: When a salt (such as sodium chloride, NaCl) is dissolved in water, it dissociates into its constituent ions. For example, NaCl dissociates into Na\u207a (sodium ions) and Cl\u207b (chloride ions).\n\n   \\[ \\text{NaCl (s)} \\rightarrow \\text{Na}^+ (\\text{aq}) + \\text{Cl}^- (\\text{aq}) \\]\n\n2. **Free Ions**: These ions are free to move around in the solution. In solid salt, the ions are fixed in a crystal lattice and cannot move, but in solution, they are dispersed throughout the water and can migrate in response to an electric field.\n\n3. **Electrolyte Solution**: A solution that contains free ions is called an electrolyte solution. Electrolytes are substances that produce ions when dissolved in a solvent, typically water, and can conduct electricity.\n\n4. **Electric Conduction**: When an electric potential (voltage) is applied across the solution, the positive ions (cations) are attracted to the negative electrode (cathode), and the negative ions (anions) are attracted to the positive electrode (anode). This movement of ions constitutes an electric current.\n\n5. **Water's Role**: Water itself is a poor conductor of electricity because it has very few ions. However, when salts or other ionic compounds dissolve in water, they increase the concentration of ions, significantly enhancing the solution's ability to conduct electricity.\n\nIn summary, a salt solution conducts electricity because the dissolved salt dissociates into free ions that can move and carry electric charge when an external electric field is applied.",
